  "prompt": "How do reporters write a report?",
  "response": "Reporters typically follow a structured approach when writing a report:\n\n1. Research and Information Gathering\n- Collect facts from multiple sources\n- Conduct interviews\n- Verify information accuracy\n- Take detailed notes\n\n2. Planning the Structure\n- Determine the story's angle\n- Organize key information\n- Create an outline\n\n3. Writing the Report\n- Use the inverted pyramid style\n- Start with the most important information\n- Answer key questions (Who, What, When, Where, Why, How)\n- Write a compelling headline\n- Include a strong lead paragraph\n\n4. Components of a News Report\n- Headline\n- Dateline\n- Lead paragraph (summary of main points)\n- Body paragraphs with supporting details\n- Quotes from sources\n- Background information\n- Conclusion\n\n5. Writing Style\n- Be objective and impartial\n- Use clear, concise language\n- Avoid personal opinions\n- Write in third person\n- Use active voice\n\n6. Editing and Fact-Checking\n- Proofread for grammar and spelling\n- Verify facts and sources\n- Ensure accuracy\n- Check for potential bias\n\n7. Final Review\n- Get editor's approval\n- Prepare for publication or broadcast",
